Default Interface Methods (C# 8.0+)

Starting with C# 8.0, interfaces can include method implementations using default interface methods

public interface ILogger
{
    void Log(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Log: {message}");
    }
}
A class implementing this interface does not have to implement Log, unless it wants to override it:
public class FileLogger : ILogger
{
    // Optional override
    public void Log(string message)
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"File Log: {message}");
    }
}

🔹 Why this was introduced
Helps add new methods to interfaces without breaking existing implementations
Useful in library evolution and versioning
Reduces need for abstract base classes in some cases

An array is the most basic collection.

int[] numbers = new int[3] { 1, 2, 3 };

Key characteristics:
Fixed size → cannot grow/shrink after creation
Type-safe → all elements must be the same type
Fastest → minimal overhead, direct memory access
Stored in contiguous memory

When to use:
When size is known and won’t change
Performance-critical scenarios

2. ArrayList (System.Collections.ArrayList)
Key characteristics:
Dynamic size
Not type-safe → can store any type (object)
Uses boxing/unboxing for value types → performance hit
Belongs to non-generic collections (legacy)
Problems:
An ArrayList is a non-generic dynamic collection (old, pre-generics).
