Key characteristics:
Dynamic size
Type-safe (generic)
No boxing/unboxing
Better performance than ArrayList
Rich API (LINQ support, etc.)


Difference between async and Task?
Task is a type (a class in .NET) that represents an asynchronous operation.

Think of it as a promise/future:

“This work will complete later, and may return a result.”
Task task = DoWorkAsync();          // no result
Task<int> taskWithResult = GetDataAsync(); // returns int

Key points:
Represents ongoing or future work
Can be:
awaited
combined (Task.WhenAll)
inspected (Status, IsCompleted, etc.)
Exists even without async keyword
async is a keyword used on methods.

It tells the compiler:

“This method contains asynchronous operations and can use await.”
public async Task<int> GetDataAsync()
{
    await Task.Delay(1000);
    return 42;
}
Key points:
Enables use of await
Changes how the method is compiled (state machine)
Usually returns:
Task
Task<T>
ValueTask<T>
(rarely void)

Feature	Task	async
What it is	A type (object)	A keyword (modifier)
Purpose	Represents async work	Enables async/await in a method
Can exist alone?	✅ Yes	❌ No (used with a method)
Returns	N/A	Usually returns Task/Task<T>

Important Relationship
async methods typically return Task
await works on Task
👉 So they are designed to work together, but are not the same.

without async
public Task<int> GetData(){
return Task.FromResult(42);
}

with async
public async Task<int> GetDataasync(){
await Task.Delay(1000);
return 42;
}

⚠️ Common Mistakes
❌ Confusing async with multithreading
async ≠ new thread
It’s about non-blocking I/O, not parallelism

❌ Using async void
public async void DoWork() // avoid
Cannot be awaited
Exceptions crash the process

👉 Use:

public async Task DoWork()


❌ Blocking on Task
var result = GetDataAsync().Result; // can cause deadlocks

👉 Prefer:

var result = await GetDataAsync();

🧠 Interview-style answer

“Task is the object that represents an asynchronous operation, while async is a keyword that allows a method to use await
and return a Task. async simplifies asynchronous programming, but the underlying abstraction is Task.”

💡 Simple analogy
Task → the delivery package
async → the system that lets you track and wait for delivery without blocking

const vs readonly keyword:
const is a A compile-time constant
public const int MaxUsers = 100;

Key characteristics:
Value is fixed at compile time
Must be assigned at declaration
Implicitly static
Only supports primitive types, string, enum

readonly :
A runtime constant (set once, but at runtime).
public readonly int MaxUsers;
Key characteristics:
Can be assigned:
At declaration
In constructor
Value can differ per instance (if not static)
Supports any type

public class Config
{
    public readonly int MaxUsers;

    public Config(int maxUsers)
    {
        MaxUsers = maxUsers;
    }
}


| Feature         | `const`                    | `readonly`                 |
| --------------- | -------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Evaluation time | Compile-time               | Runtime                    |
| Assignment      | Must assign at declaration | Declaration or constructor |
| Static          | Always static              | Can be instance or static  |
| Types allowed   | Primitive, string, enum    | Any type                   |
| Versioning      | ❌ Risky (inlined)          | ✅ Safe                     |

Use const when:
Value is truly unchanging forever
Example:
public const double Pi = 3.14159;


Use readonly when:
Value depends on:
configuration
constructor input
runtime logic
Or when exposing values from libraries

🧠 Interview one-liner

“const is a compile-time constant and is inlined, while readonly is a runtime constant that can be assigned in a constructor and is safer for versioning.”

public const int Timeout = 30;
Compile-time constant
Value is inlined into IL
Always static implicitly
Cannot change ever (even at runtime)

public static readonly int Timeout = 30;
Evaluated at runtime
Stored in memory (not inlined)
Can be assigned:
at declaration
in static constructor
